reviewText:
Firstly let's talk about the positives:

- I love the period, really nice choise, due to the fact that there were a lot of small kingdoms in Britain since the Saxon Invasion;
- The art style is amazing, even in the lowest graphics, the game still looks nice and the medium graphics don't consume a lot. The soldiers look amazing and historically accurate, the buildings are cool to gaze at;
- I really enjoy the feature of having an ever increasing map where you can build your kingdom the way you like it, aswell as being able to manipulate water, props for that one;
- As a Medieval fan, I do enjoy how you start as a small lord commanding only levies and slowly growing your army to more professional units, according to your kingdom development, the idea is there however it's dampered by the ever present and obligatory need to pay. (Point will be developed in the negative aspects);
- Finally, I enjoy the battles. They are very simple yet once you get to command a decent size force, you'll be able to see that one wrong move and it could be devastating, making it a more realistic and intense game of chess.

Now onto the negative aspects:

- I do know this is a Beta, but never have I seen a game forcing you so much to pay-to-win. After the tutorial (which is quite fast due to the bountyful gold you have at your disposal) you start to realize that the game isn't all it's cracked up to be;
- I do enjoy the battles as I've previously mentioned but they aren't as large scale as the advert promisses. Allbeit, the game is not ment to be a fully fledged Total War game, however, you are very limited to the quantities of units you can have at your disposal, this could be fixed if a fourth line could engange instead of only three, but looking at the tendency of the game I'm sure if this feature is implemented it'll require for you to pay;
- I don't like how you have to wait almost and entire day to do anything productive. Like I said, after the tutorial, the game slows down due to pay-to-win restrictions, however there are some features that can't even be bi-pased with money such as gathering resources through the facilities. I also have to mention that once you are able to withstand the patience of waiting 8h or more to harvest a resource, you only get a tiny tickle of that resource, making the waiting so insufferable;
- Once again, the pay-to-win is definatly a must in this game, due to the fact that players tend to have the most fun battling other players, but this game has a hug disadvantage for players that don't really wish to waste that much money or no money at all. If you are like me, who doesn't risk real-life money on games like this, then don't bother playing the Duel feature. Every player I have met had dozens of pay-to-win units. I don't even like how all you can do is just battle the players, you can't even influence or destroy their kingdom or even sack it. All you do is click on search play and one will be provided and you have to hope to the GODS, that you don't face a rich player.
- Finally, it seems that the game still needs to be balanced. I noticed a huge difficulty spike when I upgraded the rank of one of my levies to 2. The NPC battles just became mostly unbeatable, maybe I'm just bad but when those Viking 3 ranked units appeared agaisn't my ranked 1 swordmen and rank 2 levies, there was no need to even bet on who would win, so I just stook to Normal and Easy battles just to get a bit of fun out of the game.

Veredict:

As it stands, Total War Battles: KINGDOM, is a game full of potential for growth and could become a very enjoyable browser game and could attrack casual gamers for a more military historical style game and maybe even convince them and a few others to join the amazing Total War Community. The game is fun at first, but the huge need to pay for gold really makes the player feel bored and outraged with how it shoves in your face how you really need to pay your hard earned cash to build that tavern!
If it wasn't for this huge need to pay-to-win and a bit more variety of gameplay instead of just battling the same army over and over again until you level up a few decent levels, then, the game would actually be good, but right now it's still bare-bones, and that is visible in the Multiplayer aspect. Let's hope CA manages to fix all these problems.

I give it 4.5/10
